Ethics
Geocache listing websites have their own guidelines for acceptable geocache publications. Government agencies and others responsible for public use of land often publish guidelines for geocaching, and a "Geocacher's Creed" posted on the Internet asks participants to "avoid causing disruptions or public alarm".[65]{"citetype": "news", "title": "Geocaching puts some authorities on edge", "url": "http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10894835", "agency": "Associated Press", "accessdate": "January 2, 2009"} Generally accepted rules are to not endanger others, to minimize the impact on nature, to respect private property, and to avoid public alarm.

